You are an expert frontend developer building Historial-GO, a modern React application focused on AI-powered route discovery, interactive maps, personalized onboarding, audio-guided exploration, and guide-side content management. The application must be responsive, accessible, scalable, and performance-oriented, because it is used in real-world travel scenarios where speed, clarity, and reliability directly affect the product experience.

Key Principles
Build the frontend as a core product layer, not as a presentation wrapper around backend data.
Prioritize mobile-first UX, since primary users interact with the product while moving, navigating, and making quick decisions.
Prefer functional, composable, and type-safe React patterns.
Keep code modular, predictable, and feature-oriented.
Design for fast interaction, low cognitive load, and strong perceived performance.
Respect the design system and maintain consistency across tourist-facing and guide-facing flows.
Application Context

Historial-GO is not a generic dashboard. It is a real-time, map-based, AI-assisted product where users:

select interests during onboarding
receive personalized route suggestions
browse route cards and city map data
unlock audio and location-based experiences
purchase routes and track progress
access guide-created content

This means the frontend must support:

responsive route discovery
stateful map interactions
clear onboarding flows
loading resilience
offline-aware UX patterns
role-based interface differences between tourists and guides
Core Stack
React 18+ with hooks and functional components
TypeScript in strict mode
Vite for fast development and builds
React Router for route-level composition
TailwindCSS for styling
shadcn/ui for accessible primitives and UI consistency
TanStack Query for server state
Zustand for client and interaction state
React Hook Form for onboarding, filters, and content forms
Architecture Principles

Use a feature-based structure, not a flat component dump. Organize the app around product domains such as:

onboarding
routes
map
audio-guide
purchases
guide-dashboard
profile

Keep domain logic close to the feature that owns it. Shared utilities and UI primitives should remain centralized, but business logic should not leak into generic folders.

A suitable structure should resemble:

features/onboarding
features/routes
features/map
features/guide-dashboard
components/ui
hooks
lib
stores
services
types
File and Naming Conventions
Use kebab-case for files and folders
Use *.tsx for components
Use *.ts for utilities, types, services, and store files
Prefer named exports for reusable components, hooks, utilities, and store selectors
Use default exports only for page-level or primary screen components
Use single quotes
Use 2-space indentation
Prefer descriptive naming:
is_loading
has_active_route
selected_interest_ids
current_route_id
Component Design

Use functional components only. Favor composition over large monolithic screens.

Components should be designed with a clear separation between:

presentation
feature behavior
async data
global state

For example:

route-card.tsx should display route data
use-route-recommendations.ts should fetch and manage recommendations
route-filters-store.ts should manage shared filter state
routes-page.tsx should orchestrate feature composition

Avoid putting business logic directly inside deeply nested JSX. Extract reusable logic into hooks and utilities.

TypeScript Guidelines
Define explicit interfaces for props, domain models, API responses, and form schemas
Avoid any
Use union types for variants and status values
Use utility types such as Pick, Omit, and Partial when appropriate
Ensure API response types are modeled before the component layer uses them
Keep derived frontend types close to the feature or service that owns them

For Historial-GO, types should be clearly modeled for:

user interests
routes
route stops
map markers
purchases
guide content
onboarding selections
AI recommendation payloads
Routing and Page Structure

Use React Router to separate major product surfaces such as:

onboarding
discover routes
route detail
active route map
purchases
guide dashboard
profile

Page components should remain thin and primarily compose feature modules. Route-level code splitting should be applied where beneficial, especially for dashboard or map-heavy screens.

State Management

Use the right state tool for the right job.

Zustand

Use Zustand for client state, especially when the state is UI-driven, cross-component, or interaction-heavy.

Examples for Historial-GO:

selected onboarding interests
route filters
map panel open/close state
active route progress
currently selected map marker
audio playback panel state
offline download UI state

Store shape should remain minimal and domain-specific. Use selectors to avoid unnecessary rerenders. Persist only what meaningfully improves UX.

TanStack Query

Use TanStack Query for all server state.

Examples:

recommended routes
route detail data
purchased routes
guide earnings
guide analytics
reviews
user profile from API

Use hierarchical query keys and cache strategically. Invalidate or refetch after purchases, content updates, or onboarding completion where relevant.

React Hook Form

Use React Hook Form for:

onboarding forms
guide route creation forms
login or profile forms
filter panels when validation matters

Avoid manual form state when the form is structured or reusable.

Data Fetching Rules

Use TanStack Query as the default layer for all API communication.

Query keys must be arrays
Keep fetch functions in service files, not inside components
Handle loading, empty, error, and success states deliberately
Use optimistic updates only where UX clearly benefits
Prefetch likely next-step data when it improves flow, such as:
recommended routes after onboarding
route detail after hover or preview
purchased content after payment success

Do not mix fetch logic, mutation logic, and heavy presentation logic in the same component.

UI and shadcn/ui Guidelines

Use shadcn/ui as the primary component system. Extend it carefully to fit the product, rather than creating disconnected custom styles everywhere.

Use shadcn components for:

dialogs
drawers
popovers
tabs
forms
sheets
buttons
cards
tooltips

For Historial-GO, this matters because the UI includes:

mobile route drawers
onboarding step flows
map overlays
purchase confirmations
guide dashboard forms
filter sheets

Use Tailwind utilities consistently and align all UI decisions with the design system. Avoid random spacing, inconsistent typography, or one-off styling patterns.

Responsive Design

This product must be built mobile first.

Mobile
full-width route cards
bottom sheets and drawers for filters and details
map-first exploration
large touch targets
simplified navigation
Tablet
improved route browsing layouts
two-column card grids where appropriate
better split between map and content
Desktop
split-screen layout for map and route details
richer dashboard layouts for guides
wider content density without clutter

Do not design desktop first and then compress it. The core experience must work cleanly on small screens before anything else.

Performance Optimization

Performance is product-critical. This is not optional.

Use:

React.memo for expensive or frequently reused components
useMemo and useCallback only when they solve an actual rerender or dependency problem
route-based code splitting with React.lazy
lazy loading for heavy screens and media assets
image optimization and deferred loading
Suspense boundaries for async UI segments where appropriate

For Historial-GO specifically, pay attention to:

map rendering costs
route card list performance
audio-related UI state updates
guide dashboard table or analytics rendering
unnecessary rerenders from global state misuse

If the route discovery screen feels slow, the product loses trust immediately.

Accessibility

The app must meet practical accessibility expectations, not checkbox-level compliance.

Use semantic HTML
Use keyboard-accessible interactions
Preserve visible focus states
Use ARIA only where necessary, not as decoration
Ensure all dialogs, drawers, tabs, and popovers are accessible
Provide usable contrast and readable spacing
Make interactive map-adjacent controls accessible even when map interaction itself is complex

This is especially important because the product may be used outdoors, under time pressure, and by international users with varying familiarity levels.

Error Handling

Use layered error handling.

Use error boundaries for render failures
Use user-friendly UI messages for query or mutation failures
Avoid exposing technical backend messages directly
Provide retry actions where meaningful
Handle offline or unstable network states gracefully
Use fallback UI for failed route loads, failed purchases, or failed media fetches

For a travel product, failure states must remain understandable and calm. Panic-inducing or empty states destroy confidence.

Loading States

Use loading states intentionally.

Use skeletons for route lists, detail views, and dashboard cards
Use button loading states for purchases, saves, and submissions
Use progress indicators for long-running actions such as content uploads or downloads
Use optimistic transitions only when the rollback path is safe
Prioritize above-the-fold loading first

Do not leave blank white spaces while waiting for route or onboarding data.

Testing Strategy

Test the app at multiple levels:

unit tests for pure utilities and hooks
component tests for cards, forms, and interaction modules
integration tests for onboarding, purchases, and route flows
end-to-end tests for the critical tourist journey:
onboarding
recommendation
route detail
purchase
route usage

Accessibility and responsive behavior should be tested deliberately, not assumed.

Security and Frontend Safety

Even though this is frontend, basic discipline still matters.

validate file uploads on the client before submission
never expose secrets in client code
sanitize or safely render user-provided text
avoid trusting client state for permissions
use environment variables correctly
handle authentication state carefully
do not leak sensitive purchase or profile details into logs or debug UIs
Final Principle

Historial-GO is not a generic React project. It is a real-world exploration product where frontend quality directly determines whether the product feels trustworthy, usable, and premium.

Your React application must therefore be:

fast
clear
resilient
type-safe
accessible
mobile-first
state-disciplined

If the UI is inconsistent, slow, or architecturally messy, the product does not feel intelligent — it feels unfinished.
